<div id="nodeDecoration"><div id="headerContent"><h1 id="nodeTitle">1.2 Características generales del aprendizaje en la etapa de educación infantil</h1></div></div>
<div class="iDevice_wrapper FreeTextIdevice" id="id62">
<div class="iDevice emphasis0">
<div id="ta62_85" class="block iDevice_content">
<p>Desde que un niño nace hasta que termina su primera etapa educativa obligatoria se produce un gran número de transformaciones que afectan tanto al cuerpo como a la mente.</p>
<p>A continuación se resumen las principales transformaciones motoras, lingüísticas y afectivo sociales.</p>
<p><strong>AGE : 0-1</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION:</strong></p>
<p>- They start to focus their sight on objects and people.</p>
<p>- They can sit up without help.</p>
<p>- They can grab objects with their fingers (9 months).</p>
<p>- They can stand on their feet with help.</p>
<p>- They can walk with help (12 months).</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION:</strong></p>
<p>- They start using their vocal cords and organs by crying and shouting (0-6 months).</p>
<p>- They produce single syllabes without sense (6-8 months).</p>
<p>- They produce single syllabes with sense (8-12 months).</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They feel insecure.</p>
<p>- They need the constant presence of their mothers or known people.</p>
<p>- They start learning and discovering the world through all their senses.</p>
<p>- They like to play alone.</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 1-2</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION:</strong></p>
<p><strong>- </strong>They can walk without help (12-15 months).</p>
<p>- They can scribble with a pencil (15-18 months).</p>
<p>- They can climb stairs with help (15-18 months).</p>
<p>- They have difficulty with turning or stopping suddenly (16-19 months).</p>
<p>- They can go down the stairs with help (18-24 months).</p>
<p>- They can use their feet to kick an object (ball, etc).</p>
<p>- They can go up and down stairs without help (24 months)</p>
<p>- They can draw vertical lines (24 months)-</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p><strong>- </strong>They can understand most of their parent´s speech.</p>
<p>- They can utter some simple meanigful words.</p>
<p>- They start producig grammatically incorrect sentences.</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They cannot tell the difference between reality and fiction.</p>
<p>- They start using their memory.</p>
<p>- They ate impatient and they all want the things they like at once.</p>
<p>- They start taking on hygienic habits.</p>
<p>- They are very stubborn.</p>
<p>- Thet are selfish.</p>
<p>- They like to play alone.</p>
<p>- They are very enthusiastic.</p>
<p>- They like learning.</p>
<p>- They do not have a sense of time or space (right, left, etc).</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 2-3</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION:</strong></p>
<p>- They can jump 30 cm high (2&amp;1/2 years).</p>
<p>- They can skip (2 years and 2 months).</p>
<p>- They can stand on one foot for a short period of time (2 years and 6 months).</p>
<p>- They can draw horizontal lines and crosses (2 years and 6 months).</p>
<p>- They can tip-toe.</p>
<p>- They can catch a ball with open arms.</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p>- They understand practically everything they hear.</p>
<p>- They learn new vocabulary very fast.</p>
<p>- They can orally express what they like.</p>
<p>- If they do not know the words, they invent new words.</p>
<p>- They make many grammar mistakes.</p>
<p>- They can start with activities which prepare them for reading and writing.</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They start thinking in a symbolic way.</p>
<p>- They feel both very self-sufficient and helpless.</p>
<p>- Their character is very unstable.</p>
<p>- They love playing.</p>
<p>- They learn very fast but they forget very quickly.</p>
<p>- They understand in/ out/in front/behind.</p>
<p>- They can tell the difference between day and night.</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 3-4</strong></p>
<p>BODY COORDINATION:</p>
<p>- They can draw circles.</p>
<p>- Jump down from a certain height with feet together.</p>
<p>- They can hope.</p>
<p>- They can clothe and unclothe themselves with help.</p>
<p>- They can walk sideways and backwards (3 and 1/2 years).</p>
<p>- They can kick a ball more than 10 m.</p>
<p>- They can catch a big ball bending their arms.</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p>- They can understand almost everything in their mother tongue, and are able to figure out the meaning of words and expressions in a second or foreign language.</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They accept more and more social rules.</p>
<p>- They like playing with other children.</p>
<p>- They start having their own personality.</p>
<p>- They can feel fear, and have nightmares.</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 4-5</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION</strong></p>
<p>- They can clothe and unclothe themselves without help.</p>
<p>- They can button and unbutton things.</p>
<p>- They can stand on one foot more than 10 seconds.</p>
<p>- They can catch a smaller ball bending their arms.</p>
<p>- They can draw simple geometrical figures.</p>
<p>- They can kick a ball with strength and precision.</p>
<p>- They can run and jump (more than 1 m) at the same time (4 years and 8 months).</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p>- They understand everything.</p>
<p>- They can still have some pronunciation problems, but are able to correct them.</p>
<p>- They are curious about new words, and they learn very fast from their parents or teachers, media, etc.</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They start being able to control their feelings and behaviours.</p>
<p>- They can express their own feelings.</p>
<p>- They start feeling that they belong to a group.</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 5-6</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION</strong></p>
<p>- They can catch a bounced ball at waist level.</p>
<p>- They can run 30 m in 10 seconds.</p>
<p>- They can catch a ball with elbows tucked in.</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p>- They use grammar almost correctly.</p>
<p>- They start reading and writing.</p>
<p>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</p>
<p>- Children imitate adult´s behaviours.</p>
<p>- Relationships with classmates and friends and more and more important.</p>
<p></p>
<p><strong>AGE: 6-7</strong></p>
<p><strong>BODY COORDINATION</strong></p>
<p>- They can draw squares, rectangles, triangles, oblongs, and diamonds.</p>
<p>- They can walk in a straight line.</p>
<p><strong>LANGUAGE ACQUISITION</strong></p>
<p>- They do not make any mistakes with grammar.</p>
<p>- They can read and write.</p>
<p><strong>INDIVIDUAL FEATURES AND INTELLIGENCE</strong></p>
<p>- They admire teachers and parents.</p>
<p>- They can work very well in groups.</p>
<p></p>
<p>Todo maestro de idiomas debe ser consciente de lo que puede esperar de sus propios alumnos antes de acercar al niño de educación infantil a una segunda o tercera lengua. En este sentido, ha de saber hasta qué punto el alumno será capaz de adquirir contenidos fonológicos, morfológicos, semánticos y sintácticos de otra lengua, si todavía no han sido adquiridos en la lengua materna. Por lo tanto, procede analizar brevemente cómo se adquiere la lengua materna.</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
